 worked to craft his racial identity in a world that saw him simply as “black,” and how his mental and physical health problems shaped his career. Gabbard sets aside the myth-making and convincingly argues that Charles Mingus created a unique language of emotions—and not just in music. Capturing many essential moments in jazz history anew, Better Git It in Your Soul will fascinate anyone who cares about jazz, African American history, and the artist’s life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDouble bassistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJazz musicianszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh  a20th century musicians.  aafrican american history.  aafrican american musicians.  aafrican american.  abandleader.  abiography.  abiracial musicians.  ablack musicians.  acharles mingus jazz.  aclassically trained jazz musician.  ahistory of jazz.  aimprovisation.  aimprovised jazz.  ajazz composers.  ajazz history.  ajazz musicians.  ajazz performers.  ajazz.  alanguage for emotions.  amidwest jazz.  amusic history.  amusical genius.  arace and identity in jazz scene.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052026037540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096374040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963740/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY